Package sprouts.impl

Class SequenceDiff

java.lang.Object
sprouts.impl.SequenceDiff
public final class SequenceDiff extends Object
A SequenceDiff object holds meta information about a Tuple instance that describes how the Tuple was transformed from its previous state.

So for example, if the Tuple.removeFirst(int) method was called with a count of 3, then the resulting Tuple will internally maintain a SequenceDiff instance with a change() == SequenceChange.REMOVE, index() == 0 and size() == 3.

The purpose of this class is to provides meta information specifically for efficient binding and change propagation to other data structures, such as UI components, databases, or network services.
More specifically, it allows a change listener to synchronize to the Tuple state changes in an optimized way, by only updating its own target data structure according to the information provided by the SequenceDiff instance.

In practice, you would only do this optimized sync to a tuple after first checking if isDirectSuccessorOf(SequenceDiff) is true, and then update the target data structure with the information provided by the SequenceDiff instance.

Although this class is specifically designed for the Tuple type, you may also use this class with other immutable value based sequenced collections to do optimized synchronization to state changes.

  • Method Details

    • of

      public static SequenceDiff of(Tuple<?> origin, SequenceChange change, int index, int size)
      Creates a new SequenceDiff instance from a source Tuple instance and how it was changed to a new state.
      If the given Tuple instance is a SequenceDiffOwner, then this method will attempt to retrieve the previous SequenceDiff instance and create a new SequenceDiff instance that is a successor of the previous one.
      If the Tuple instance is not a SequenceDiffOwner, then a new SequenceDiff instance is created with a new lineage.
      Parameters:
      origin - The Tuple instance to create a SequenceDiff for.
      change - The type of change that occurred in the Tuple.
      index - The index at which the change occurred in the Tuple.
      size - The number of items that were affected by the change in the Tuple.
      Returns:
      A new SequenceDiff instance with the given parameters.

    • initial

      public static SequenceDiff initial()
      Creates a new SequenceDiff instance that represents the initial state of a Tuple instance.
      This is used to create a SequenceDiff instance that represents the state of an initial Tuple instance and at the beginning of a potential chain of transformations.
      Returns:
      A new SequenceDiff instance that represents the initial state of a Tuple.

    • isDirectSuccessorOf

      public boolean isDirectSuccessorOf(SequenceDiff other)
      The successor of a SequenceDiff is computed deterministically from a previous SequenceDiff. To ensure that this line of succession is unique, the signature of the a SequenceDiff is based on a lineage, succession and hashcode number.

      We can use this information to determine if this SequenceDiff is a successor of another SequenceDiff instance in a linear chain of transformations. Which is exactly what this method does.

      When trying to do optimized synchronization to Tuple state changes, don't forget to call this method before using change(), index(), and size() to update the target data structure.

      Parameters:
      other - The SequenceDiff to check if this SequenceDiff is a successor of.
      Returns:
      True if this SequenceDiff is a successor of the given SequenceDiff.

    • version

      public Version version()
      The version of the Tuple state to which this SequenceDiff belongs. This is used as a bases for determining if this SequenceDiff is a successor of another SequenceDiff instance in a linear chain of transformations. (See isDirectSuccessorOf(SequenceDiff)).
      Returns:
      The version of the Tuple state.

    • signature

      public long signature()
      The signature of this SequenceDiff instance. This is a hash code that is based on the version(), change(), index(), size(), and the signature of the previous SequenceDiff instance in the chain of transformations.
      Returns:
      The signature of this SequenceDiff instance.
